<br>
We got a new director of the library and she envisions things differently than a lot of us do, and she's making changes. Some of them are ok, but some of them .. not so ok.<br>
<br>
The ones I do not like involve students being able to drink from items that spill easy. We used to have a policy that you could not have glass or plastic or anything unless it was a spill proof reusable cup.<br>
<br>
Too many folks bring in those flimsy coffee cups that the lid pops off of if you knock it over.<br>
<br>
Course, now we allow anything as long as its spill proof and those flimsy cups technically seem to apply -- now we got lots of coffee stains on the carpet.<br>
<br>
Folks are still not supposed to eat, but they sneak it in more now ever than before.<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
And thats not all, but i will not go into every change because the point I want to make is this:<br>
<br>
Things change. We may not always like those changes though, unless we were the instigator of that change. Most of us are comfortable, and change upsets that, and it makes us uncomfortable, and causes stress -- until we get used to the change and embrace it. Change is necessary to keep us active, on our toes and involved. If there was never any change, life would grow pretty boring.<br>
<br>
Everyone should be allowed to impliment changes in their life, and if a group of people by majority agree to form a change then by all means they should be allowed to do this.<br>
<br>
There is nothing wrong with resisting those changes, but if you cannot embrace them, or at least adjust to them, then you should remove yourself from having to negotiate with that change.<br>
<br>
